<header class="header">
  <h1>Short-Season Winter Squash Varieties</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Choose winter squash that can fully mature before frost ends the vines.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Short-season winter squash varieties are usually smaller or earlier types that can mature and cure with less seasonal risk than large, long-vine storage squash.</strong>
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Answer</h2>
  <p>
    In short seasons, choose winter squash varieties with earlier maturity and moderate fruit size. The crop needs enough time not only to grow fruit, but also to reach full maturity for flavor and storage.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Safest choices:</strong> delicata, small butternut types, and compact early squash</li>
    <li><strong>Higher risk:</strong> large long-season storage squash</li>
    <li><strong>Main challenge:</strong> fruit may form but fail to fully mature before frost</li>
    <li><strong>Best strategy:</strong> choose earlier varieties and avoid late planting</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Makes Winter Squash Short-Season Friendly?</h2>
  <p>
    Winter squash is different from zucchini. You are not harvesting young tender fruit every few days. You need the fruit to mature on the vine, develop good eating quality, and in many cases cure for storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Smaller fruit and earlier maturity improve the odds. Large squash can be impressive, but they often need a longer warm season to finish properly.
  </p>
  <ul class="tight">
    <li><strong>Moderate fruit size:</strong> easier to mature before frost.</li>
    <li><strong>Earlier maturity:</strong> gives more buffer for curing and harvest timing.</li>
    <li><strong>Healthy vines:</strong> poor early growth delays fruit set.</li>
    <li><strong>Storage goals:</strong> storage squash needs full maturity, not just full size.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Winter Squash Varieties to Compare</h2>
  <p>
    These profiles help compare early maturity, fruit size, and storage usefulness.
  </p>
  <ul>
