  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Full Size Is Not the Same as Full Maturity</h2>
  <p>
    Winter squash can look large before it is fully mature. Flavor, storage quality, and rind development improve when the fruit has enough time to finish on the vine.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is why short-season gardeners should avoid using fruit size alone as the harvest signal. A variety that finishes earlier gives you more room for proper maturity before frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Choosing Short-Season Winter Squash</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Choosing large squash first:</strong> bigger fruit usually needs more time.</li>
    <li><strong>Planting too late:</strong> late vines may set fruit but not mature it.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring curing needs:</strong> storage quality depends on maturity and handling.</li>
    <li><strong>Overcrowding vines:</strong> stressed plants may set later and finish poorly.</li>
    <li><strong>Expecting butternuts to behave like zucchini:</strong> winter squash needs a full-season plan.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Best Strategy for Short Seasons</h2>
  <p>
    Start with smaller or earlier winter squash varieties before trying long-season storage types. In cool climates, give the crop the warmest garden spot and avoid delaying planting after conditions are safe.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Plan Around Your Local Season</h2>
  <p>
    Winter squash success depends on warm growth, timely fruit set, and enough season left for maturity. Check both your frost window and seasonal heat before choosing a variety.
